<promed@promedmail.org>
[This case is mentioned in the 10 Jan 2005 posting (20050110.0079).
Mucormycosis, sometimes referred to as zygomycosis, is the name given
to infections caused by fungi of the order Mucorales including
organisms of species _Rhizopus_, _Rhizomucor_, _Mucor_, and
_Cunninghamella_. They are quite ubiquitous in the environment,
including being isolated from nonsterile adhesive tape and tongue
depressors and being linked to human infection (1, 2).
This widespread distribution is balanced by the low virulence of the
fungi in humans, generally limited to individuals with severe
immunoincompetence or diabetes. Additionally, however, as described
in the above posting, contamination of devitalized tissue during
trauma can result in mucormycosis even without other risk factors (3).
1. Gartenberg G, Bottone EJ, Keusch GT, et al: Hospital-acquired
mucormycosis (_Rhizopus rhizopodiformis_) of skin and subcutaneous
tissue. N Engl J Med 1978;299:1115-17.
2. Mitchell SJ, Gray J, Morgan MEI. et al: Nosocomial infection with
_Rhizopus microsporus_ in preterm infants: Association with wooden
tongue depressors. Lancet 1996;34:441-43.
3. Vainrub B, Macareno H, Mandel S, et al: Wound zygomycosis
(mucormycosis) in otherwise healthy adults. Am J Med 1988;84:546-48.
- Mod.LL]
